  "prompt": "What are some things new employees should know going into their first day at AIG?",
  "response": "Okay, here's a breakdown of essential information new employees should know before starting their first day at AIG. This covers practicalities, company culture, and expectations:\n\n**I. Before Day One: Preparation & Mindset**\n\n*   **Review Offer Letter & Onboarding Materials:**  Re-familiarize yourself with your offer letter, any onboarding documents sent beforehand (employee handbook, benefits information, etc.), and any pre-assigned training. Knowing what to expect and what's expected of you reduces anxiety.\n*   **Research AIG:** Go beyond the surface.  Understand AIG's core businesses (insurance, retirement, etc.), recent news, strategic initiatives, and key leaders. AIG is a large organization, so understanding how your role fits within the bigger picture is valuable.\n    *   **AIG's Website:** (www.aig.com) is a good starting point.\n    *   **News Articles:** Search for recent articles about AIG in reputable business publications.\n    *   **AIG's Investor Relations Page:** (if you're interested) can provide insights into the company's financial performance and strategic direction.\n*   **Plan Your Commute & Attire:**  Figure out your route to the office (or your home office setup if remote).  Confirm the dress code (business casual is generally a safe bet, but ask HR if you're unsure).  Lay out your outfit the night before.\n*   **Prepare Questions:**  Jot down any questions you have about your role, the company, or the onboarding process.  It's better to ask than to remain confused.\n*   **Rest & Recharge:**  Get a good night's sleep!  Being well-rested will help you make a positive first impression and absorb information more effectively.\n*   **Set Realistic Expectations:** First days are often about introductions, paperwork, and getting your bearings. Don't expect to be fully productive immediately. Focus on learning and building relationships.\n\n**II. On Day One: Practical Matters & First Impressions**\n\n*   **Arrival Time:**  Arrive on time, or even a few minutes early.  It shows respect and professionalism.\n*   **Check-In:** Know where to check-in (HR, reception, your manager's office).  Have your ID ready.\n*   **IT Setup:**  Expect to spend time setting up your computer, email, and other systems. Be patient, and don't hesitate to ask for help if you encounter problems.\n*   **Paperwork:** Be prepared to complete HR paperwork, including tax forms, benefits enrollment, and confidentiality agreements. Bring any required documents (e.g., driver's license, social security card).\n*   **Introductions:**  Be prepared to introduce yourself to your manager, team members, and other key individuals.  Smile, make eye contact, and have a brief, professional introduction ready (name, role, and perhaps a sentence about your background or what you're looking forward to).\n*   **Office Tour:**  Take note of important locations (restrooms, break rooms, printers, etc.).\n*   **Lunch:**  Ask about lunch options. Will you be going out with the team? Is there a cafeteria?  Bring your own lunch if you're unsure.\n*   **Note-Taking:**  Bring a notebook and pen (or use a digital note-taking system) to record important information, instructions, and names.\n*   **Active Listening:**  Pay close attention to what people are saying.  Ask clarifying questions to ensure you understand.\n*   **Positive Attitude:**  Be enthusiastic, friendly, and eager to learn.\n\n**III. Company Culture & Expectations at AIG**\n\n*   **Hierarchy:** AIG is a large, established corporation, so understand that there is likely a clear organizational structure. Be respectful of seniority.\n*   **Communication:** Pay attention to how communication flows within your team and department.  Is it primarily email, instant messaging, meetings, or a combination?\n*   **Professionalism:** Maintain a professional demeanor in all interactions. Use appropriate language, dress appropriately, and be respectful of others' time and opinions.\n*   **Collaboration:** AIG values teamwork. Be willing to collaborate with colleagues and contribute to team goals.\n*   **Compliance & Ethics:** AIG places a high emphasis on compliance and ethical behavior. Be sure to understand the company's code of conduct and any relevant regulations.\n*   **Initiative:** While it's important to learn the ropes, don't be afraid to take initiative and offer suggestions.\n*   **Feedback:** Be open to receiving feedback and use it to improve your performance.  Also, don't hesitate to ask for feedback from your manager and colleagues.\n*   **Learning and Development:** AIG likely offers training and development opportunities.  Take advantage of these resources to enhance your skills and knowledge.\n*   **Networking:** Start building relationships with your colleagues. Networking can help you learn about different parts of the company and advance your career.\n*   **Work-Life Balance:** AIG is evolving its approach to work-life balance.  Inquire about policies related to flexible work arrangements, time off, and well-being programs.\n\n**IV. Specific Questions to Ask (if not already covered)**\n\n*   **\"What are the key priorities for the team/department in the next few months?\"**\n*   **\"What are the biggest challenges facing the team/department?\"**\n*   **\"What are the expectations for me in my role during the first 30/60/90 days?\"**\n*   **\"Who are the key people I should connect with outside of my immediate team?\"**\n*   **\"What is the best way to communicate with you (my manager)?\"**\n*   **\"Where can I find resources on [specific software/system/policy]?\"**\n*   **\"What opportunities are there for training and development?\"**\n*   **\"Who should I contact for IT support?\"**\n*   **\"What is the process for requesting time off?\"**\n\n**V. Post-Day One**\n\n*   **Reflect:** Take some time to reflect on your first day. What did you learn? What went well? What could you have done better?\n*   **Follow Up:** Send thank-you emails to your manager and anyone else who was particularly helpful.\n*   **Review Materials:** Review any onboarding materials or notes you took during the day.\n*   **Prepare for Day Two:**  Plan your commute, outfit, and any tasks you need to complete.\n\nBy being prepared, professional, and proactive, you can make a great first impression and set yourself up for success at AIG. Good luck!\n",
